para.para.body:
Direction of the cross product vector   Given two vectors 
   \Vect{x}
 and 
   \Vect{y}
, their cross product is perpendicular to both 
   \Vect{x}
 and 
   \Vect{y}
. Moreover, the ordered triple 
   (\Vect{x},\Vect{y},\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} })
 represents the right hand orientation of 
   \RNr[3]
.

These two properties combined determine the direction of the cross product vector. (If 
                     \Vect{x}
                   and 
                     \Vect{y}
                   are parallel, then  their cross product vanishes.) Thus the only information we are missing about the cross product vector is its length ...

Length of the cross product vector   The length of 
   \CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }
 satisfies

So it is determined by the length of 
                     \Vect{x}
                  , the length of 
                     \Vect{y}
                  , and the angle between them. So it is equal to the area of the parallelogram spanned by 
                     \Vect{x}
                   and 
                     \Vect{y}
                  .
